column227: I prefer this metaphor to the gardening metaphor and the other metaphors because I feel that it is most accurate about the student-teacher relationship.  It's a give-and-take relationship where students are trained, tested, and ultimately have to stand on their own knowledge in the big games.  A teacher is not a dictator or a master, they are an educator and a coach, they are the expert in their subject and they adjust their teaching style as necessary with each topic and each student in order to reach a common goal.  Students are like athletes because work is required of them.  They are expected to be willing to be coached, to push themselves by going over the information until they've got it, and work together as a team to get through the class.  The responsibility is ultimately the students'.  This metaphor fits my experience because as a former college student, I know how much work the student has to put in to learn the material, and that a teacher's position is much more like a coach - there when you need them, willing to help but can't do it for you, and ready to give you a little push in the right direction - than like someone who is fully in control.

With the gardener metaphor, students can be like plants and can grow if they are tended to carefully.  So the teacher/gardener would see the needs of the students/plants and tend to those needs so that the students/plants can grow.  With the sculptor/clay, the teacher would be molding the students into something greater than what they were before (mere clay).  Of the two metaphors, I prefer the gardener/plants, because it fits the teacher/student relationship better.

A teacher is like a knowledgeable tour guide who can guide students through a subject and point out the important attractions and help the students/tourists understand more about them.  And the tour guide can help tourists develop a greater interest so they will want to go exploring on their own.  I like how it doesn't have the implication of responsibility that the gardener/plant and sculptor/clay metaphors have.  A tour guide shows the tourists what there is to see, and it's up to the tourists to decide how much they want to get out of the tour.
